 A signal $x(t)$ is DSB-modulated using a cosine at 1 kHz, giving
  $y(t)=x(t)\cos(2\pi 1000t)$. Then $y(t)$ is DSB-demodulated using a
  sine at 1 kHz, giving $z(t)=y(t)\sin(2\pi 1000t)$. What is $z(t)$?

    <ul class="answers">
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q18ai"/><input type="radio" name="q18" value="a" id="q18a"><label for="q18a">$z(t)=0$</label><br>       
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q18bi"/><input type="radio" name="q18" value="b" id="q18b"><label for="q18b">$z(t)=x(t)/2$ </label><br>          
