<div class="question25"  style="display:none;">
<p class="question">
<h2><b><span style="color:red;">Test 6.25</span></b></h2>
A 7-Hz sinusoid is sampled at 10 samples/s and reconstructed
  from its samples using a brickwall lowpass filter. The frequency of
  the reconstructed sinusoid is:
    <ul class="answers">
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q25ai"/><input type="radio" name="q25" value="a" id="q25a"><label for="q25a">3 Hz</label><br>       
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q25bi"/><input type="radio" name="q25" value="b" id="q25b"><label for="q25b">5 Hz</label><br>          
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q25ci"/><input type="radio" name="q25" value="c" id="q25c"><label for="q25c">7 Hz</label><br>        
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q25di"/><input type="radio" name="q25" value="d" id="q25d"><label for="q25d">10 Hz</label><br>
    </ul>
    
<script>
  document.getElementById('q25a').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q25b').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q25c').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q25d').checked = false;
answer_value[25] = "a";
</script>
<div id="question25_answer" style="display:none;">
<span style="color:red;">Solution:</span><br>The sampled signal has components
at 
$$
\{\pm 7\pm 20k\}=\pm\{3,7,10,13,\dots\} \rm Hz, 
$$ for integers $k$. The lowpass filter has cutoff frequency
$\frac{10}{2}=5$ Hz, leaving $\pm 3$ Hz.
</div>
<br>
</div>





<div class="question26"  style="display:none;">
<p class="question">
<h2><b><span style="color:red;">Test 6.26</span></b></h2>
A signal whose spectrum $=0$ for $|f|>12$ Hz is sampled at 20
  samples/s.  Using a brick-wall lowpass filter, the original signal
  spectrum can be reconstructed from its samples up to how many Hz:
    <ul class="answers">
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q26ai"/><input type="radio" name="q26" value="a" id="q26a"><label for="q26a">0 (none of it)</label><br>       
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q26bi"/><input type="radio" name="q26" value="b" id="q26b"><label for="q26b">2</label><br>          
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q26ci"/><input type="radio" name="q26" value="c" id="q26c"><label for="q26c">4</label><br>        
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q26di"/><input type="radio" name="q26" value="d" id="q26d"><label for="q26d">8</label><br>
    </ul>
    
<script>
  document.getElementById('q26a').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q26b').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q26c').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q26d').checked = false;
answer_value[26] = "d";
</script>
<div id="question26_answer" style="display:none;">
<span style="color:red;">Solution:</span><br>Baseband: -12&lt;f&lt;12 Hz. First
image: 8&lt;f&lt;32 Hz, where $20-12=8$ and $20+12=32$.  So -8&lt;f&lt;8 kHz
of baseband is unaffected by the first image.

Recall that ''images'' are copies of the original (baseband) spectrum
induced by sampling.
</div>
<br>
</div>





<div class="question27"  style="display:none;">
<p class="question">
<h2><b><span style="color:red;">Test 6.27</span></b></h2>
Signal $x(t)=\cos(2\pi 4t)$ is ideally sampled at 1 sample/s,
  then filtered by a brick-wall lowpass filter with cutoff frequency
  3.5 Hz and gain 1/2:

$\cos(2\pi 4t)\to$<div style="display: inline-block;border: 2px solid black;padding:2px;">1 sample/s</div>$\to$<div style="display: inline-block;border: 2px solid black;padding:2px;">
$\bf H (\omega)=\cases{1/2, & $0<|\omega|<7\pi$\cr 0, & $|\omega|>7\pi$}$</div>$\to
  y(t)$. What is the expression for $y(t)$?
    <ul class="answers">
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q27ai"/><input type="radio" name="q27" value="a" id="q27a"><label for="q27a">$y(t)=0$</label><br>       
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q27bi"/><input type="radio" name="q27" value="b" id="q27b"><label for="q27b">$y(t)=\cos(2\pi t)$</label><br>          
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q27ci"/><input type="radio" name="q27" value="c" id="q27c"><label for="q27c">$y(t)=\cos(2\pi t)+\cos(4\pi t)$ </label><br>        
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q27di"/><input type="radio" name="q27" value="d" id="q27d"><label for="q27d">$y(t)=\cos(2\pi t)+\cos(4\pi t)+\cos(6\pi t)$</label><br>
    </ul>
    
<script>
  document.getElementById('q27a').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q27b').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q27c').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q27d').checked = false;
answer_value[27] = "d";
</script>
<div id="question27_answer" style="display:none;">
<span style="color:red;">Solution:</span><br>Sampling a 4-Hz signal at 1
sample/s creates doubled copies at $\pm\{0,1,2,3,\dots\}$ Hz. The
filter eliminates 0 Hz (did you notice that?) and copies above 3.5 Hz.
</div>
<br>
</div>





<div class="question28"  style="display:none;">
<p class="question">
<h2><b><span style="color:red;">Test 6.28</span></b></h2>
A signal $x(t)$ has the Fourier transform $\bf X (2\pi f)$ plotted
  below.<br>
<img src="figs/fig6_28q.jpg" width="500"/>
<br>
The minimum sampling rate for which $x(t)$ can be reconstructed from
its samples is:
    <ul class="answers">
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q28ai"/><input type="radio" name="q28" value="a" id="q28a"><label for="q28a">6000 samples/s </label><br>       
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q28bi"/><input type="radio" name="q28" value="b" id="q28b"><label for="q28b">4000 samples/s</label><br>          
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q28ci"/><input type="radio" name="q28" value="c" id="q28c"><label for="q28c">3000 samples/s</label><br>        
<img src="blank.png" width="15" id="q28di"/><input type="radio" name="q28" value="d" id="q28d"><label for="q28d">2000 samples/s</label><br>
    </ul>
    
<script>
  document.getElementById('q28a').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q28b').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q28c').checked = false;
  document.getElementById('q28d').checked = false;
answer_value[28] = "d";
</script>
<div id="question28_answer" style="display:none;">
<span style="color:red;">Solution:</span><br>The spectrum of the sampled signal
when sampled at 2000 samples/s:
<br>
<img src="figs/fig6_28s.jpg" width="100%"/>
<br>
A bandpass filter with passband 2&lt;|f|&lt;3 kHz will recover $x(t)$ from
its samples.

This is an example of bandpass sampling. The spectrum is really only 1
kHz wide.
</div>
<br>
</div>
















<script type="text/javascript">
    var i;
    var count=0;
    var scores = [];
    var nclicks = [];
    var nquestions = 28;
    for (i = 1; i < nquestions+1; i++) {
        scores[i] = 0;
        nclicks[i]=0;
    }// endfor

$(function(){

 var i;
 var count=0;
  //var debug=1;// true
  var debug=0;// false
  if( debug == 1) {
    for (i=1; i<nquestions+1;i++){
       count++;
       $(".question"+(i)).css("display", "block");
       $(".score"+(i)).css("display", "table-row");
    } //endfor   
  }//endif

 // display a random selection of 5 questions
 var thresh=6./(nquestions-1.);
 while (debug==0 && count < 5) {
   for (i = 1; i < nquestions+1; i++) {
     if(Math.random() <thresh && count<5) { 
       count++;
       $(".question"+(i)).css("display", "block");
       $(".score"+(i)).css("display", "table-row");
     }
   }//endfor
   if(count<5){
      count=0;
      for (i = 1; i < nquestions+1; i++) {
       $(".question"+(i)).css("display", "none");
       $(".score"+(i)).css("display", "none");          
      }
   }
 }//end while

});
</script>





















